body:
We have some fairly large javascript bundles (~10-20 MB with sourcemaps added) which we include in some of our webviews. These views run remotely because they communicate with remote extensions (which perform things like file search and version control).

However currently initial load takes a very noticeable amount of time when opening the webview. I traced code to find it's all spent on a remote filesystem read operation.

Request:
I'd like for workspace extension to be able to either:

1) (ideal) declare resources that should be pre-fetched when running remotely, so initial javascript load is instant
2) have a mechanism to cache vscode-resources so they don't need to be re-downloaded on each open (e.g. by setting `?cache=true` on the URI)

Here's an example patch that does a very simple caching and makes resource reloading much faster (option 2 above):
```
diff --git a/src/vs/workbench/contrib/webview/common/resourceLoader.ts b/src/vs/workbench/contrib/webview/common/resourceLoader.ts
index ea33db2e26..74a905be71 100644
--- a/src/vs/workbench/contrib/webview/common/resourceLoader.ts
+++ b/src/vs/workbench/contrib/webview/common/resourceLoader.ts
@@ -7,7 +7,7 @@ import { VSBuffer } from 'vs/base/common/buffer';
 import { sep } from 'vs/base/common/path';
 import { startsWith, endsWith } from 'vs/base/common/strings';
 import { URI } from 'vs/base/common/uri';
-import { IFileService } from 'vs/platform/files/common/files';
+import { IFileService, IFileContent } from 'vs/platform/files/common/files';
 import { REMOTE_HOST_SCHEME } from 'vs/platform/remote/common/remoteHosts';
 import { getWebviewContentMimeType } from 'vs/workbench/contrib/webview/common/mimeTypes';
 
@@ -25,14 +25,20 @@ const AccessDenied = new class { readonly type = 'access-denied'; };
 
 type LocalResourceResponse = Success | typeof Failed | typeof AccessDenied;
 
+const cache: Map<string, Promise<IFileContent>> = new Map();
+
 async function resolveContent(
 	fileService: IFileService,
 	resource: URI,
 	mime: string
 ): Promise<LocalResourceResponse> {
 	try {
-		const contents = await fileService.readFile(resource);
-		return new Success(contents.value, mime);
+		let contentsPromise = cache.get(resource.toString());
+		if (contentsPromise === undefined) {
+			contentsPromise = fileService.readFile(resource);
+			cache.set(resource.toString(), contentsPromise);
+		}
+		return new Success((await contentsPromise).value, mime);
 	} catch (err) {
 		console.log(err);
 		return Failed;

